 <RESPONSE>
 <VARNAME>C14033_1</VARNAME>
 <SENTIMENT>Positive</SENTIMENT>
 <VALUE>First, the Reception Desk was welcoming and quietly said my name so as to not announce it to the entire waiting room. Do you understand this. :-) Patients are more likely not to want their name announced to the entire waiting room upon entering. I appreciate this. Secondly, Dr Vandermolen always demonstrates "team" by first introducing me to his assistant. This gives value to the patient and his assistant as well as himself because we all want a continuum of care. I see this in the assistant taking notes; him discussing and listening to my concerns. At the appointment end Dr Vandermolen directed me checkout with a Happy New Year and his assistant showed me the way. Finally, as I stood at checkout I was quickly called to the counter making a future appointment in seconds. Since this was a questionnaire for this last appointment I was not able to add the RN/blood draw experience.</VALUE>
 </RESPONSE>
 <RESPONSE>
 <VARNAME>CMPTNAME</VARNAME>
 <SENTIMENT></SENTIMENT>
 <VALUE>Christi Holbrook</VALUE>
 </RESPONSE>
 <RESPONSE>
 <VARNAME>CMPTPHON</VARNAME>
 <SENTIMENT></SENTIMENT>
 <VALUE>2093273668</VALUE>
 </RESPONSE>
 <RESPONSE>
 <VARNAME>SECTACCE</VARNAME>
 <SENTIMENT>Negative</SENTIMENT>
 <VALUE>My appointment was cancelled by the office July. I was not rescheduled. I did not hear from the office. I allowed time to go before I called in for another appointment till December.</VALUE>
 </RESPONSE>
 <RESPONSE>
 <VARNAME>SECTCARE</VARNAME>
 <SENTIMENT>Positive</SENTIMENT>
 <VALUE>I've appreciated the incredibly good care Dr Vandermolen has given me from the first appointment visit. He has shown me an engaging, intelligent, keen minded professional interest in my healthcare. I have given his name as a referral to my family, friends, acquaintances and patients. I value his doctor referrals addressing medical needs. More importantly, he has clear discussions with me about my plan of care and involves me in these discussions. One of the most important attributes of communication is listening and so it is the same with a Dr and Patient communicating. Dr Vandermolen has this gift coupled with leaving me with "hope" every single time I leave his office.</VALUE>
 </RESPONSE>
 <RESPONSE>
 <VARNAME>SECTMOVT</VARNAME>
 <SENTIMENT>Positive</SENTIMENT>
 <VALUE>Waiting room is pleasant. Receptionists are professional.</VALUE>
 </RESPONSE>
 <RESPONSE>
 <VARNAME>SECTNURS</VARNAME>
 <SENTIMENT>Mixed</SENTIMENT>
 <VALUE>In the three years at Keck with Dr Vandermolen I've absolutely always had the most professional, engaging, confident RN experience. Until this last time. When I was called to the door I stood there waiting. The RN did not welcome me; nor ask my name or DOB; just "come in here". The person was kind, however, very detached. My vitals were taken. Blood drawn with the tour-a-cut left on my upper arm till she was completely done with the blood draws. I've the fattest veins always ready for a blood draw! Then, the person asked my DOB and name. I asked for a copy of my blood drawn results. I was responded with a yes. No conversation at all. Lolol I was asked to follow the person to the room. The door shut. Minutes later I was handed my results with no words; no smile; I said thank you. There was no intensional unkindness, but rather a detachment to a connection with the patient.</VALUE>
 </RESPONSE>
 <RESPONSE>
 <VARNAME>SECTOVER</VARNAME>
 <SENTIMENT>Positive</SENTIMENT>
 <VALUE>The office has a predictable process of managing patient care from the time we enter that door. My experience from the moment I sign in is welcoming and most receptionists remember the patients.</VALUE>
 </RESPONSE>
 <RESPONSE>
 <VARNAME>SECTPERS</VARNAME>
 <SENTIMENT>Positive</SENTIMENT>
 <VALUE>The only observation I can give you here is my experience everyone is treated the same equally.</VALUE>
 </RESPONSE>
 </COMMENTS>
