 <COMMENTS>
 <RESPONSE>
 <VARNAME>ROPEN18</VARNAME>
 <SENTIMENT>Mixed</SENTIMENT>
 <VALUE>Overall, I feel that all nurses and doctors would be greatly helped by a communication course. Most of them would walk in the room and talk very loudly to the air, not to the patient. Without any observing of the patient, they walk in and very loudly talk and explain complicated things to a patient in pain or drugged. It was a constant parade of interruptions of loud communications with no observation if the patient was ready to receive the communication. There were a few nurses who were much better at this, but overall, the communication was just a loud communication into the air with no idea that there was a patient there to receive it. I think they should all learn how to look at the patient, then with the correct volume, the correct velocity and the correct words, communicate to the patient who is right there with words that can be received and understood by the patient in their current state. Communicate to the patient, not to the air or the room. There was one Asian person who came into the room on the 5th floor to take a reading of the heart and he was very rude. He had no idea how to communicate to a patient. He was not understandable and when my husband asked me to translate, he got mad and said he didn't need a translator. The truth is he totally needed a translator not because of his language but because he had no ability to communicate effectively to a patient. There is a huge difference in communciating TO a person and just talking. Jack in ICU was very good at communication. And also a nurse, in ICU I think her name was Jay. Those 2 did an excellent job of talking TO the patient.</VALUE>
 </RESPONSE>
 </COMMENTS>
