 <VARNAME>SECTCARE</VARNAME>
 <SENTIMENT>Mixed</SENTIMENT>
 <VALUE>To be honest I left there feeling worse about my pending surgery than before I arrived. I was hoping the feel a little more assured and informed. It was less than a stellar consultation to my surprise. I am being honest because you stated that this is confidential. I am a nurse I have worked in surgery for 35 years for background. Dr Yun came highly recommend by an employee of my sister who had bilateral hips done by Dr Yun. She recommended him to 5 other people who then had their hips done by him. All are extremely happy with their results!! He also has great online reviews at a glance. My sister, Suzanne's former employer, went with me so she could meet Dr Yun whom she'd heard so much about. We are both very friendly and social. We were looking forward to it. Dr Yun came into the room with a smile and immediately started to recite a reassurance talk that I am sure he tells all patients about how no one wants this procedure but at some point it becomes necessary when it gets worse etc. I was grateful to hear it anit was in a friendly tone. But when I began to ask him questions his tone got more agitated and impatient. I asked him for example about the general consent emailed to me to sign ahead of the visit which stated that Arcadia Hospital is a teaching facility and there would be Residents present in the OR and may be participating. I forgot the exact wording. I asked if that's true and he waived it off and said it would only be faculty and he acknowledged that the consent says that but it's not true, followed by saying, "I don't like Residents!" That's verbatim. And he repeated that statement a little later after I said that I did like Residents but was just surprised that they were at a private hospital.He explained that he instructed them in a classroom setting and that's all. I told him I had one big concern and that's that I worked at LA General hospital and many of my peers leave and go to other hospitals like Arcadia and I had been told several worked in surgery there. A hip replacement exposes you physically. You're naked and very compromised. I have been in the OR with many. And I don't want my coworkers in the OR with me for that reason. And that I would especially not want my male coworkers in the room during my surgery. Dr Yun seemed agitated and Annoyed with me at this point and said he would assure me that they would be respectful of my privacy and want to end it there. But wat does that mean??? I wanted reassurance that wee could keep male nurses and techs out of my room to insure my privacy because it would be awkward and embarrassing to go back and work with them after. I think this is understandable and I am sure even Dr Yun would not want his own female nurses in the room with him if he had to have a surgery that he had to be exposed in. Anyone should empathize with this! He repeated that they would respect my privacy in an irritated tone. His answer was a non answer. I wanted to know how he could accomplish this. Could we request all female nurses and techs and was this really possible? He was very tightly wound and irritated with me at this point and sa he would make the request. Then in a condescending tone he asked me if it was ok that his PA was male? And if it was ok if the anesthesiologist was male? I said of course Beto thought I made it understood that I was only concerned about my peers the nurses and techs I knew and may be working with in the future. He seemed angry with me and said that he had tried to reassure me and if I didn't like it I could go to a different doctor or even go out of state to have it done . He looked angry and stormed out of the room leaving the door open without saying another word. I felt a little dick to my stomach because this spiraled into such an awkward situation. My sister and I looked at each other stunned. We didn't know if we were supposed to leave. We sat there for 5 minutes and no one came in so we gather our thoughts and left the room to exit. We were yelled at down the hall by the staff to stop and go back in because their scheduling person was going to come talk to us. So we went back in. My head was spinning and I was unsure what to do but she was very nice and made the split decision to move forward. What if the next surgeon wasn't any different? And obviously I needed the surgery and I have no doubt that Dr Yun is a great surgeon. But I was very disappointed in how the consultation went. I did not expect at all. Please do not repeat this to him or at least not until my surgery is over with. I don't want to jeopardize my surgery any further. He did write me a very well worded doctors note and I am grateful for that, I am hoping our relationship will improve and smooth over. I just don't see any reason for the anger. My own take on it is that he's only comfortable when he's in control and he's doing all the talking and he doesn't like to be questioned ( I did also ask him if I could possibly wear a skimpy thong intraoperatively for assurance because I know that people walk in and out of ORs to borrow things and give lunch breaks etc) He was steamed and said no! I asked him what prep solution he uses and if the leg is prepped circumferentially. He answers but was unhappy about my questions. All in all he was just very irritated with me. And I personally think it was unfounded. I am just hoping this goes well and I can power through this. I will have to see how this all goes to know if I would recommend him and or Arcadia hospital. I am hoping for a great result and we'll see.</VALUE>
 </RESPONSE>
